Anonymization¶

The dataset's features can be categorized into the following

Qualitative data: ID, Tweet URL*, Group, Collector, Category, Topic, Keywords, Account handle*, Account name*, Account bio*, Account type, Location, Tweet*, Tweet Translated, Tweet Type, Content type, Reasoning, Remarks

Quantitative data: Timestamp, Joined, Following, Followers, Date posted, Likes, Replies, Retweets, Quote Tweets

Note that the features above marked with * are identifiable features. In order to anonymize the data, we have to remove these features.

In [27]:
dataset['Account code'] = pd.factorize(raw_dataset['Account handle'])[0]

identifiable_columns = ['Tweet URL', 'Account handle', 'Account name', 'Account bio', 'Tweet']
dataset.drop(columns=identifiable_columns, inplace=True)

Try making some code for quick-checking formats:

In [46]:
counts = 0
for date in dataset['Date posted']: #check formats of date
  is_wrong = False
  date_posted = date.strip().split()
  date_format = date_posted[0].split('/')
  time = date_posted[1].split(':')
  if (len(date_format) != 3 or len(time) != 2 or  #if formats are right they should have the right length
    int(date_format[0]) > 31 or #low level check of day
    int(date_format[1]) > 12 or #check month
    int(date_format[2]) > 22 or #check year upper bound
    int(date_format[2]) < 16 or #check year lower bound
    int(time[0]) > 24 or #check hour
    int(time[1]) > 59): #check minutes
      print(date)
      is_wrong = True

  if is_wrong: counts += 1

print("Number of wrong formatted cells under Date posted column:", counts)

Number of wrong formatted cells under Date posted column: 0

Formatting of relevant columns looks correct.

Interpolated graphs¶

The following graphs have interpolated values:

In [35]:
dataset['Month'] = pd.to_datetime(dataset['Date posted'], dayfirst=True).dt.to_period('M').dt.to_timestamp() #get year and month

index = pd.period_range(start='2016-01', end='2022-12', freq='M').to_timestamp() #get range of years
#debug code for checking the column contents
#with pd.option_context('display.max_rows', None, 'display.max_columns', None):
#    print(dataset['Month'].value_counts().reindex(index).astype(pd.Int8Dtype()))

plt.figure(figsize=(20, 6))

line = dataset['Month'].value_counts().reindex(index)#get the count of tweets per month, reindex it to include missing months, fill missing months with 0s, then convert count to integer to revert NaN promotion

#check a few interpolation methods
line.fillna(0).plot.line(label='Not interpolated')
line.interpolate().plot.line(label='Linear')
line.interpolate(method='bfill').plot.line(label='Backfill')
line.interpolate(method='nearest').plot.line(label='Nearest')
line.interpolate(method='quadratic').plot.line(label='Quadratic')
line.interpolate(method='cubic').plot.line(label='Cubic')
line.interpolate(method='piecewise_polynomial').plot.line(label='Piecewise_polynomials')

# Adds line for target month
# plt.axvline(x=pd.Period('2017-09', freq='M').to_timestamp(), color='red', linestyle='--')

plt.axhline(y=0, color='gray', linestyle='--', alpha=0.25)

plt.legend(loc="upper right")
plt.xlabel('Time (resolution: months)')
plt.ylabel('Tweet Frequency')
plt.xticks(index)
plt.title('Frequency of Mis/Disinformation Tweets per Month on President Duterte\'s War on Drugs')
plt.tight_layout()

Interpolating by year doesn't matter, because each year has a value and .interpolate() only fills NaN values.

Any method of interpolation which creates a smooth curve (quadratic, cubic) creates negative values in order to preserve peaks in the values. The positive interpolations have pros and cons as follows:

  1. Linear: Simplistic and unrealistic; it is difficult to believe that a straight line represents values with any accuracy
  2. Nearest: As data values are few and far between (such as many gaps between the points) getting the nearest point to use as a value of interpolation causes repetitive counts.
  3. Backfill: Similar downsides to Nearest interpolation
  4. Piecewise polynomials: does not interpolate last and starting values due to constraints of interpolation (requires two points)

From the above, perhaps piecewise polynomials are most promising:

In [36]:
line.fillna(0).plot.line(label='Not interpolated')
line.interpolate(method='piecewise_polynomial').plot.line(label='Piecewise polynomial interpolation')

plt.axhline(y=0, color='gray', linestyle='--', alpha=0.25)

plt.legend(loc="upper right")
plt.xlabel('Time (resolution: months)')
plt.ylabel('Tweet Frequency')
plt.title('Frequency of Mis/Disinformation Tweets per Month on President Duterte\'s War on Drugs')
plt.tight_layout()

Binned graphs¶

One idea is to bin the graphs by event. Because the event relevant to the study is Kian delos Santos's death, we can separate the times around the event (arbitrarily, from August 2017 to October 2017). There are two possible ways to bin the remaining tweets: either all in their own bin, or two separate bins (one before the event and one after).

Starting with the first (one bin for the event and one bin for otherwise):

In [38]:
event_bin = dataset[(dataset['Month'] <= "2017-10") & (dataset['Month'] >= "2017-08")].shape[0] #number of tweets found within 08-2017 and 10-2018
non_event_bin = dataset[(dataset['Month'] > "2017-10") | (dataset['Month'] < "2017-08")].shape[0]

d = {'Bin': ['From Aug. 2017 to Sept. 2017', 'Outside Aug. 2017 to Sept. 2017'], 'count': [event_bin, non_event_bin]}
small_dataset = pd.DataFrame(data=d).set_index('Bin')
small_dataset.plot.bar(edgecolor = 'black')

plt.xlabel('Bin')
plt.ylabel('Tweet Frequency')
plt.title('Bar graph for Amount of Mis/Disinformation Tweets on President Duterte\'s War on Drugs')

plt.xticks(rotation=6)

print("Total tweets:",event_bin + non_event_bin)

Total tweets: 155

Now the second (three bins: before, during, after):

In [39]:
event_bin = dataset[(dataset['Month'] <= "2017-10") & (dataset['Month'] >= "2017-08")].shape[0] #number of tweets found within 08-2017 and 10-2017
after_bin = dataset[(dataset['Month'] > "2017-10")].shape[0]
before_bin = dataset[(dataset['Month'] < "2017-08")].shape[0]

d = {'Bin': ['Before Aug. 2017', 'From Aug. 2017 to Sept. 2017', 'After Sept. 2017'], 'count': [before_bin, event_bin, after_bin]}
small_dataset = pd.DataFrame(data=d).set_index('Bin')
small_dataset.plot.bar(width=1, edgecolor = "black")

plt.xlabel('Bin')
plt.ylabel('Tweet Frequency')
plt.title('Histogram for Amount of Mis/Disinformation Tweets on President Duterte\'s War on Drugs')

plt.xticks(rotation=10)

print("Total tweets:", event_bin + after_bin + before_bin)

Total tweets: 155

The above binned graphs have bins of unequal time ranges (that is, the event bin is 2 months long while every other bin is much longer), thus further into the project clustering may be used to bin the timeframes instead. The above graphs serve more as quick tests.

for code, count in zip(account_codes, account_counts):

It appears that the mean amount of tweets an account has in the dataset is approximately 1.12, though the majority of the accounts in the dataset are unique. Note that 12 accounts appear in the dataset more than once.
